In the case of Le Père Goriot, he changed a number of the characters into persons from other novels he had written, and added new passages.In the first book edition, the novel was divided into seven chapters:

In the first volume:Une Pension bourgeoise (A Bourgeois Boarding House);
Les Deux Visites (The Two Visits);
L'Entrée dans le Monde (The Entrance into the World);
In the second volume:L'Entrée dans le Monde (Suite) [The Entrance into the World (Continuation)];
Trompe-la-Mort (Cheat-the-Death, Death-Dodger, or Dare-Devil);
Les Deux Filles (The Two Daughters);
La Mort du Père (The Father's Death).The character Eugène de Rastignac had appeared as an old man in Balzac's earlier philosophical fantasy novel La Peau de chagrin.
